It's important to know how many examples we have for each class when we work with a new dataset.

  • What is the percentage of entries in the dataset for each class? **[0.1]**

    0.96 % = Anomalous Data

99.04% = Non-Anomalous Data

  • Is this data considered balanced or unbalanced? Why is this the case? [0.1]

    The dataset is Unbalanced because there is a huge difference between the percentages of the Anomalous and 
Non-Anomalous data. 
If it were to be a Balanced dataset, the percentages would've been somewhat equal with a minor variance of 2 %.

  • Why is balance/imbalance important? How might this class ditribution affect a KNN classifier for example, which we explored in Project 1? [0.5]

    When a dataset is balanced, it means that the number of samples in each class is roughly the same. In this case, the model can learn to distinguish between the classes more easily because there are no biases towards any 
particular class. On the other hand, when a dataset is imbalanced, it means that the number of samples in each 
class is not equal, which can lead to several issues:

Biased model: If one class has many more samples than the other, the model might become biased towards the 
majority class and struggle to classify samples from the minority class.

Poor generalization: If the model is trained on an imbalanced dataset and evaluated on a balanced dataset, it 
might not generalize well because it was not exposed to enough examples from the minority class during training.

Misleading evaluation metrics: If the dataset is imbalanced and the evaluation metric used is accuracy, the 
model might achieve high accuracy simply by predicting the majority class all the time, without actually 
learning to distinguish between the classes.

In the case of a KNN classifier, the class distribution of the dataset can affect the classification performance in several ways. For example:

When dealing with imbalanced datasets, KNN classifiers can face challenges such as unbalanced distances, where 
the distance between samples from the minority class might be larger than those from the majority class, making classification harder. Additionally, the neighborhood size can be biased towards the majority class, leading to misclassification of minority class samples. Hyperparameter tuning, such as adjusting the number of neighbors or the distance metric, may be necessary to achieve good performance on the minority class.

  • What metrics should we use to evaluate a model in such cases? [0.2]

    The metrics that we would use to evaluate this model is F1 score and/or Recall. The higher the F-1 Score, the 
better the model. 
The F-1 score balances precision and recall on the True Positive class. For an unbalanced dataset, even if the 
model misclassifies a large number of the minor class into the major class, the precision rate is likely to be 
very high. 
The recall rate = TP/(TP+FN). Decreasing the number of FN (False Negatives (Misclassified data points)), 
will increase the recall rate and should probably increase the accuracy of classifiing the minor class 
correctly.

Part 2: One Gaussian model with Single feature: [2 Marks]¶

We'll start by making a prediction using a single feature of our dataset at a time.

Please note that we only use V features in our model.

a. Fitting regardless of class:

  1. Fit a single Gaussian distribution on a single feature of the full training dataset (both classes) using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1.
  2. Compute AUC (Area under the ROC Curve) based on sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture.score_samples on both the full training set and validation set (including both classes).
  3. Repeat the above steps for each of the features and present your findings in a table. [0.3]
  4. Find the best 3 features to distinguish anomalous forests from non-anomalous forests based on the AUC of the validation set. [0.2]
  5. Make a prediction based on a model's scores: If the score_samples is lower than a threshold, we consider that forest as an anomaly. Find an optimal threshold that maximizes the F1 Score of the validation set for each of those 3 features separately. (Do not check every possible value for threshold, come up with a faster way!) Compute F1 score using sklearn.metrics.f1_score. [0.5]
  6. Report Precision, Recall and F1 score on both training and validation set in a table using the threshold you found in previous step.
  7. Report the complexity of your method (Big O notation) for determining the optimal threshold.[0.3]

b. Fitting based on class:

  1. Pick 3 features that had the best AUC in Part 2a.
  2. repeat part 2a to compute AUC, F1 score, Precision and Recall when you fit a Gaussian only on non-anomalous forests in the training set in step 1 (instead of all the forests).

# Step 5 Functions - Defined before the main calling, to avoid recursivity.

# Find F1 Score for different Thresholds
def f1_score_by_threshold(x, y):
    
    # Setting the Threshold by the 1st Quantile with 300 steps.
    threshold = np.arange(np.min(x), 
                          np.quantile(x,.25),
                          (np.quantile(x,.25) - np.min(x)) / 300) # Found by looking at the max validation accuracy (Tried with 100 - 500 steps)
    
    # List Comprehension for the "Prediction List"
    prediction = [[(lambda score, thr: 1 if (score < thr) else 0)(score, thr) for score in x] for thr in threshold]
    
    # Prediction 'y_pred' dataframe.
    dict_pred = {'Threshold': threshold, 'Prediction': prediction}
    df_pred = pd.DataFrame(dict_pred)
    
    # Calculate F1 Score & + to Dataframe
    f1_score_list = [f1_score(y, y_pred) for y_pred in df_pred['Prediction']]
    df_pred['F1 Score'] = f1_score_list
    
    # Return the new Dataframe with F1 Score, Predicted value and Threshold value respectively.
    return df_pred

# Best Threshold and Maximized F1 Score
def best_f1_score_and_threshold(df_pred):
    best = df_pred.loc[df_pred['F1 Score'].idxmax()]
    return best['Threshold'], best['Prediction'], best['F1 Score']

# Step 6 Functions

# Find Precision and Recall for the maximized F1 Score with it's corresponding Threshold
def precision_recall_f1_with_threshold(x, y, best_thr):
    
    # List Comprehension for the "Prediction List"
    pred = [(lambda score, thr: 1 if (score < thr) else 0)(score, best_thr) for score in x]
    
    # Return Precision and Recall with the Best Threshold and Maximised F1 Score.
    return precision_score(y, pred), recall_score(y, pred), f1_score(y, pred)

# Step 1 - 3

features = [f for f in df.columns if not 'id' in f and not 'Anomaly' in f]

# Lists for AUC outputs
AUC_train_single_feat_list = []
AUC_val_single_feat_list = []

for feature in features:
    
    # Gaussian model for single feature
    gm_single = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, random_state = 0)
    
    # Fitting a single normal distribution on a single feature
    gm_single.fit(X_train[feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    
    # Find scores on Train set and Validation set
    train_score = gm_single.score_samples(X_train[feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    val_score = gm_single.score_samples(X_val[feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
     
    # Find AUC on Train set and Validation set and add to Lists
    AUC_train_single_feat_list.append(roc_auc_score(y_train, -1 * train_score))
    AUC_val_single_feat_list.append(roc_auc_score(y_val, -1 * val_score))

# AUC Outputs as DataFrame
AUC_list = {'Train Set AUC': AUC_train_single_feat_list, 'Validation Set AUC': AUC_val_single_feat_list}
df_AUC = pd.DataFrame(AUC_list, index = df.columns[0:10])
print('AUC for Train and Validation Sets')
show.display(df_AUC)

# Step 4

# Top 3 Features based on Validation set AUC
max_feat_name = df_AUC.nlargest(3, 'Validation Set AUC')
print('Top 3 Features')
show.display(max_feat_name)
max_feat_name = max_feat_name.index

# Step 5 - 6

# Find thresholds that Maximize F1 score
best_threshold_list = []

# Lists for F1 score, Precision, & Recall for Validation Set
best_val_f1_score_list = []
best_val_precision_list = []
best_val_recall_list = []

# Lists for F1 score, Precision, & Recall for Train Set
best_train_f1_score_list = []
best_train_precision_list = []
best_train_recall_list = []

for feature in max_feat_name:
    
    # Gaussian model for single feature
    gm_single = GaussianMixture(n_components = 1, random_state = 0)
    
    # Fitting a single normal distribution on a single feature
    gm_single.fit(X_train[feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    
    # Finding the scores in Train and Validation set
    train_score = gm_single.score_samples(X_train[feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    val_score = gm_single.score_samples(X_val[feature].values.reshape(-1, 1))
    
    # Finding the F1 Score and respective Thresholds from Validation set only.
    df_thr_based_f1_pred = f1_score_by_threshold(val_score, y_val)
    
    # Threshold, Prediction and F1 Score when F1 Score is maximized
    best_threshold, best_pred, best_f1_val = best_f1_score_and_threshold(df_thr_based_f1_pred)
    
    # Appending Optimized Threshhold to List
    best_threshold_list.append(best_threshold)
    
    # Precision and Recall for Max F1 Scores and Best Thresholds for Train and Validation set
    best_train_precision, best_train_recall, best_train_f1_score = precision_recall_f1_with_threshold(train_score, y_train, best_threshold)
    best_val_precision, best_val_recall, best_val_f1_score = precision_recall_f1_with_threshold(val_score, y_val, best_threshold)
    
    # Train Set Lists
    best_train_f1_score_list.append(best_train_f1_score) # F1 Score
    best_train_precision_list.append(best_train_precision) # Precision
    best_train_recall_list.append(best_train_recall) # Recall
    
    # Validation Set Lists
    best_val_f1_score_list.append(best_f1_val) # F1 Score
    best_val_precision_list.append(best_val_precision) # Precision
    best_val_recall_list.append(best_val_recall) # Recall
    
# Best Threshold with corresponding F1 Scores

Report the complexity of your method (Big O notation) for determining the optimal threshold.[0.3]

The time complexity of the given code depends on the complexity of the functions used. Here is the Big O notation for each of the functions:

Defined Functions

  • f1_score_by_threshold: O(n2 + n)
  • best_f1_score_and_threshold: O(n)
  • precision_recall_f1_with_threshold: O(n)

Steps 1 - 3

  • Features for loop: O(n)
  • Gaussian Models for loop: O(n)

Step 4

  • nlargest (Sorting method): O(nlogn)

Step 5 - 6

  • Features for loop for Models: O(n)
    • f1_score_by_threshold: O(n^2 + n)
    • best_f1_score_and_threshold: O(n)
    • precision_recall_f1_with_threshold: O(n)
    • precision_recall_f1_with_threshold: O(n)

Overall Model Complexity = O(n2) + O(n) + O(n) + O(n) + O(n) + O(nlogon) + O(n)(O(n2) + O(n) + O(n) + O(n))

Results ----> O(n3) + 4.O(n2) + 4.O(n) + O(nlogn)

Therefore, the overall time complexity of the given code is O(n3) because the most complex function used in the code is the combination of the for loop of 'Models with features' in which the 'f1_score_by_threshold' is called. However, this is an upper bound and the actual time complexity may be lower, depending on the size of the data and the specific parameters used.

How would class imbalance affect any classifier in general (apart from just a KNN)? [0.2]

Class imbalance can affect any classifier, not just KNN, in several ways:

  1. Bias: Class imbalance can lead to a bias in the classifier's predictions towards the majority class. This is because the classifier tends to classify most instances as belonging to the majority class, even if they belong to the minority class. This bias can result in poor performance for the minority class, as the classifier may miss many instances of the minority class, leading to False Negatives.

  2. Low accuracy: A classifier trained on an imbalanced dataset may have low accuracy overall, as it may perform well on the majority class but poorly on the minority class.

  3. Sensitivity and specificity: Class imbalance can also affect the sensitivity and specificity of a classifier. Sensitivity measures the proportion of True Positives that are correctly identified, while Specificity measures the proportion of True Negatives that are correctly identified. An imbalanced dataset can cause a classifier to have high sensitivity but low specificity, or vice versa due to the high amount of False Negatives.

  4. Overfitting: An imbalanced dataset can also lead to overfitting, where the classifier becomes too specialized to the training data and performs poorly on new data. This can happen if the classifier learns to overemphasize the majority class and ignores the minority class, leading to poor generalization.

In summary, class imbalance can affect any classifier in several ways, leading to biased predictions, low accuracy, poor sensitivity and specificity, and overfitting. It is important to address class imbalance in the dataset to improve the performance of the classifier.

def AUC_Train_Val_comparison(X_train, y_train, feature_1, feature_2, n = 1):
    
    # Lists for AUC scores
    AUC_train_multiple_feat_list = []
    AUC_val_multiple_feat_list = []
    
    # Gaussian model for multiple features
    gm_multiple = GaussianMixture(n_components = n, random_state = 0) # Model
    gm_multiple.fit(X_train[[feature_1, feature_2]].values) # Model Fitting
    
    # AUC for Train and Validation sets
    train_score = gm_multiple.score_samples(X_train[[feature_1, feature_2]].values) # Train set
    val_score = gm_multiple.score_samples(X_val[[feature_1, feature_2]].values) # Validation set
    
    # Appending Lists for Train and Validation sets
    AUC_train_multiple_feat_list.append(roc_auc_score(y_train, -1 * train_score)) # Train set
    AUC_val_multiple_feat_list.append(roc_auc_score(y_val, -1 * val_score)) # Validation set
    
    # convert all AUC outputs into table(dataframe form)
    df_auc_gm_mul = pd.DataFrame({'Gaussian Components': n, 
                                  'Train set AUC': AUC_train_multiple_feat_list, 
                                  'Validation set AUC': AUC_val_multiple_feat_list},
                                 index = [str(feature_1 + ' & ' + feature_2)])
    print('AUC Scores for ' + feature_1 + ' & ' + feature_2)
    return show.display(df_auc_gm_mul)

Part 4: Two Gaussian model with single feature. [3 Marks]¶

Now we will use two separate distributions for anomalous and non-anomalous forests.

  1. Fit a Gaussian distribution ($G_1$) on a feature of non-anomalous forests using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1. [0.5]
  2. Fit another Gaussian distribution ($G_2$) on the same feature but for anomalous forests using sklearn.mixture.GaussianMixture when n_components=1. [0.5]
  3. Compute the score samples ($S$) for both $G_1$ and $G_2$ on the validation set to get $S_1$ and $S_2$, respectively. [0.5]
  4. Find an optimal $c$ (a real number) that maximizes validation set F1 Score for a model such that if $S_1 < c \times S_2$, the forest is classified as anomalous. For example, if $c=1$ we could say that if $S_2$ is greater than $S_1$, ($S_1$<$S_2$) then the forest is anomalous (the forest belongs to the $G_2$ distribution which represents anomalous forests). For start consider $c$ in $[0,10]$ with steps of 0.1, you can change this window in your experiments if needed. [0.5]
  5. Repeat the steps above for all the features. What is the best F1 Score, Precision and Recall that you get for training and validation? Which feature and what c? Show your results in a table. [0.5]
  6. Can we report AUC for this model? Why? [0.5]

# Empty  Validation table list for Storage
validation_table = []

for feature in features:
    
    # Filtering the data for Non-Anomalous and Anomalous type.
    X_train_na_feat = X_train[feature][y_train==0].values.reshape(-1,1) # Non-Anomalous
    X_train_a_feat = X_train[feature][y_train==1].values.reshape(-1,1) # Anomalous
    
    # Gaussian Models for Non-Anomalous and Anomalous Data respectively.
    G1 = GaussianMixture(n_components=1, random_state=0) # Non-Anomalous
    G2 = GaussianMixture(n_components=1, random_state=0) # Anomalous

    # Fitting the models on the Train set respectively.
    G1.fit(X_train_na_feat)
    G2.fit(X_train_a_feat)

    # AUC scores on Validation set only.
    S1 = G1.score_samples(X_val[feature].values.reshape(-1,1)) # Non-Anomalous
    S2 = G2.score_samples(X_val[feature].values.reshape(-1,1)) # Anomalous
    
    # Variables initialised to 0
    c = 0
    max_c = 0
    max_f1 = 0
    precision = 0
    recall = 0

    while(c <= 10):
        f1 = f1_score(y_val, S1 < (c * S2))
        if(max_f1 < f1):
            max_f1 = f1
            max_c = c
            precision = precision_score(y_val, S1 < (c * S2))
            recall = recall_score(y_val, S1 < (c * S2))
        c += 0.1

    validation_table.append([max_c, max_f1, recall, precision])

validation_table = pd.DataFrame(np.array(validation_table), 
                                columns = ['c', 'Validation F1 Score', 'Validation Recall', 'Validation Precision'],
                                index = features)

def multivariate_gm_multiple(X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val, X_test, y_test, features, n, table, test_mode=False, c_test = 0):
    
    if test_mode: # if test_mode is True: (Default = False)
        
        # Filtering the data for Non-Anomalous and Anomalous type.
        X_train_na_feat = X_train[features][y_train==0].values # Non-Anomalous
        X_train_a_feat = X_train[features][y_train==1].values # Anomalous
        
        # Gaussian Models for Non-Anomalous and Anomalous Data respectively.
        GMM_1 = GaussianMixture(n_components=1, random_state=0) # Non-Anomalous
        GMM_2 = GaussianMixture(n_components=n, random_state=0) # Anomalous
        
        # Fitting the models on the Train set respectively.
        GMM_1.fit(X_train_na_feat)
        GMM_2.fit(X_train_a_feat)
        
        # AUC scores on Test set only.
        S1_test = GMM_1.score_samples(X_test[features].values) # Non-Anomalous
        S2_test = GMM_2.score_samples(X_test[features].values) # Anomalous
        
        # Variables initialised to 0
        max_f1_test = 0 # Validation
        precision_test = 0 # Validation
        recall_test = 0 # Validation
    
        max_f1_test = f1_score(y_test, S1_test < (c_test * S2_test))
        precision_test = precision_score(y_test, S1_test < (c_test * S2_test))
        recall_test = recall_score(y_test, S1_test < (c_test * S2_test))
            
        table.append([len(features), n, c_test, 
                      precision_test, recall_test, max_f1_test])
        
    else:
        
        # Filtering the data for Non-Anomalous and Anomalous type.
        X_train_na_feat = X_train[features][y_train==0].values # Non-Anomalous
        X_train_a_feat = X_train[features][y_train==1].values # Anomalous
        
        # Gaussian Models for Non-Anomalous and Anomalous Data respectively.
        GMM_1 = GaussianMixture(n_components=1, random_state=0) # Non-Anomalous
        GMM_2 = GaussianMixture(n_components=n, random_state=0) # Anomalous
        
        # Fitting the models on the Train set respectively.
        GMM_1.fit(X_train_na_feat)
        GMM_2.fit(X_train_a_feat)
    
        # AUC scores on Train set only.
        S1_train = GMM_1.score_samples(X_train[features].values) # Non-Anomalous
        S2_train = GMM_2.score_samples(X_train[features].values) # Anomalous
        
        # AUC scores on Validation set only.
        S1_val = GMM_1.score_samples(X_val[features].values) # Non-Anomalous
        S2_val = GMM_2.score_samples(X_val[features].values) # Anomalous
        
        # Variables initialised to 0
        c_val = 0 # Validation
        c_train = 0 # Train
        
        max_f1_val = 0 # Validation
        max_f1_train = 0 # Train
        
        precision_val = 0 # Validation
        precision_train = 0 # Train
        
        recall_val = 0 # Validation
        recall_train = 0 # Train
    
        while(c_val <= 10):
            f1 = f1_score(y_val, S1_val < (c_val * S2_val))
            if(max_f1_val < f1):
                max_f1_val = f1
                c_train = c_val
                precision_val = precision_score(y_val, S1_val < (c_val * S2_val))
                recall_val = recall_score(y_val, S1_val < (c_val * S2_val))
            c_val += 0.1
    
        max_f1_train = f1_score(y_train, S1_train < (c_train * S2_train))
        precision_train = precision_score(y_train, S1_train < (c_train * S2_train))
        recall_train = recall_score(y_train, S1_train < (c_train * S2_train))
        
        table.append([len(features), n, c_train, 
                      precision_train, recall_train, max_f1_train, 
                      precision_val, recall_val, max_f1_val])

Why does it make sense to have multiple components for the anomalous forests?

Having multiple components for anomalous forests makes sense because anomalous forests may have different characteristics that make them anomalous. By using multiple components in the model, we can capture the different characteristics and identify anomalous forests more accurately. In contrast, valid forests may have more uniform characteristics, so a single component model with multiple features may be sufficient to capture their properties.

Moreover, this is because non-anomalous data typically clusters together, whereas anomalous data may be scattered in different directions. If we use a single component to model anomalous data, it may only capture the most extreme instances of anomalous data, leaving out other instances that are not closely associated with this component. As a result, these other instances may be misclassified as non-anomalous data. To better capture the full range of anomalous data, it may be necessary to use multiple components.

Report the complexity of your method (Big O notation) for determining the optimal threshold.[0.3]

The time complexity of the given code depends on the complexity of the functions used. Here is the Big O notation for each of the functions:

Defined Functions

  • f1_score_by_threshold: O(n2 + n)
  • best_f1_score_and_threshold: O(n)
  • precision_recall_f1_with_threshold: O(n)

Steps 1 - 3

  • Features for loop: O(n)
  • Gaussian Models for loop: O(n)

Step 4

  • nlargest (Sorting method): O(nlogn)

Step 5 - 6

  • Features for loop for Models: O(n)
    • f1_score_by_threshold: O(n^2 + n)
    • best_f1_score_and_threshold: O(n)
    • precision_recall_f1_with_threshold: O(n)
    • precision_recall_f1_with_threshold: O(n)

Overall Model Complexity = O(n2) + O(n) + O(n) + O(n) + O(n) + O(nlogon) + O(n)(O(n2) + O(n) + O(n) + O(n))

Results ----> O(n3) + 4.O(n2) + 4.O(n) + O(nlogn)

Therefore, the overall time complexity of the given code is O(n3) because the most complex function used in the code is the combination of the for loop of 'Models with features' in which the 'f1_score_by_threshold' is called. However, this is an upper bound and the actual time complexity may be lower, depending on the size of the data and the specific parameters used.
